{"title_page": "Yves Bouvier", "text_new": "{{short description|Swiss businessman and art dealer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{POV check|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = File:Yves Bouvier.jpg\n| image_size   =\n| name         = Yves Bouvier\n| caption      = Yves Bouvier\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=y|1963|09|08}}\n| birth_place  = Geneva, Switzerland\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  =\n| restingplace =\n| nationality  = Swiss\n| religion     = \n| ethnicity    = \n| residence    = Singapore\n| education    =\n| alma mater   = \n| occupation   = CEO, Natural Le Coultre\n| known for    = Businessman and art dealer\n| salary       = \n| networth     = \n| spouse       = \n| parents      = Jean-Jacques Bouvier\n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Yves Bouvier''' (born 8 September 1963 in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Bouvier Affair: A True Story|last=Bregman|first=Alexandra|publisher=Ingram|year=2019|isbn=1733834575|location=|pages=48}}</ref>) is a Swiss businessman and [[art dealer]] best known for his role in [[the Bouvier Affair]] that resulted in criminal charges being brought against him in France and Monaco. He was the president of Natural Le Coultre, an international company specialized in the transportation, storage, scientific analysis, and conservation of works of art, luxurious goods and other collectibles.\n\nIn September 2017, it emerged that Bouvier is under criminal investigation by Swiss authorities amid allegations that he may have evaded more than 100 million euros in taxes related to his cross-border art dealings.<ref>https://news.artnet.com/art-world/yves-bouvier-swiss-tax-charges-1072205</ref> In February 2018, meanwhile, the Geneva Prosecutor reportedly opened a new criminal investigation into Bouvier relating to an indictment on charges of fraud.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n==Early life==\nYves Bouvier is the son of Jean-Jacques Bouvier, owner of Natural Le Coultre, a 150-year-old company specialized in moving and storing goods. Yves Bouvier early developed an interest in art, and dropped out of college to join his father's company in the eighties.<ref name=fr.worldtempus.com>{{cite web|title=Natural Le Coultre, le transport au sommet de son art depuis 150 ans|url=http://fr.worldtempus.com/article/culture/publiart-natural-coultre-transport-au-sommet-son-art-150-ans-326553|publisher=WorldTempus|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\n\n===Natural Le Coultre===\nNatural Transports was formed in 1859 as a moving and furniture storage company. It later became Natural Le Coultre<ref name=fr.worldtempus.com /> in 1901, when Albert-Maurice Natural joined Emile-Etienne Le Coultre to create A. Natural, Le Coultre & Cie. The company's office was located in Geneva. The firm was mainly dealing with commodity deliveries, including fruits, equipment and Red Cross parcels during the [[World War I|First World War]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/02/08/the-bouvier-affair|title=The Art-World Insider Who Went Too Far|last=Knight|first=Sam|date=2016-02-01|access-date=2019-10-07|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/swiss-freeport-king-yves-bouvier-sells-art-storage-company-natural-le-coultre|title=Swiss freeport king Yves Bouvier sells art storage company Natural Le Coultre|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, Jean-Jacques Bouvier began an [[apprenticeship]] at Natural Le Coultre S.A. 30 years later in 1983, the Bouvier family acquired Natural Le Coultre.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1989, Jean-Jacques and Yves Bouvier formed Fine Art Transports Natural Le Coultre SA in Geneva, which provided moving and furniture storage services to the local companies. Hoping that Yves would keep leading the family business, Jean-Jacques Bouvier promoted his son to the position of assistant manager in 1995 and then managing director in 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rc.ge.ch/hrcintreport/createReport?rcentId=5750093500000066031025&lang=FR&order=R&rad=Y |title=NATURAL LE COULTRE SA : inscrite le 24 janvier 1946 : Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 anonyme |publisher=Rc.ge.ch |accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> selling the moving and furniture storage activities to a local company to focus the company on storing, moving, and preserving pieces of art.<ref name=\"bilan.ch\">{{cite web|title=Ce visionnaire qui a pari\u00e9 sur l\u2019Asie|url=http://www.bilan.ch/entreprises-les-plus-de-la-redaction/ce-visionnaire-qui-parie-sur-lasie|publisher=TIFFY&CO.|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> Yves Bouvier moved to [[Singapore]] in 2009 where he currently resides.\n\nUnder Bouvier\u2019s control, Natural Le Coultre owned 5 percent of the [[Geneva Freeport|Geneva freeport]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icomturkey.org/en/content/beleaguered-yves-bouvier-defends-himself-and-freeport-system|title=Beleaguered Yves Bouvier defends himself and freeport system {{!}} ICOM Turkey |website=icomturkey.org|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> but the company was sold to Andr\u00e9 Chenue, a [[Paris]]ian shipping firm, in 2017 for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/swiss-freeport-king-yves-bouvier-sells-art-storage-company-natural-le-coultre|title=Swiss freeport king Yves Bouvier sells art storage company Natural Le Coultre|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/27/arts/yves-bouvier-sells-his-geneva-based-art-storage-company.html|title=Yves Bouvier Sells His Geneva-based Art Storage Company|last=Bowley|first=Graham|date=2017-10-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, in line with the investigation into Bouvier\u2019s potential tax-evasion, Federal Tax Administration (FTA) officials temporarily sequestered one of Natural Le Coultre\u2019s buildings in Geneva, worth 4.5 million [[Swiss franc]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.letemps.ch/suisse/fisc-federal-enquete-yves-bouvier|title=Le fisc f\u00e9d\u00e9ral enqu\u00eate sur Yves Bouvier|date=2017-09-04|access-date=2019-10-02|language=fr|issn=1423-3967}}</ref>\n\n===Freeport facilities===\nBouvier exported the freeport concept, and in 2005, expanded his business model abroad<ref>{{cite web|title=Yves Bouvier: une ascension fulgurante dans le monde de l\u2019art|url=http://www.letemps.ch/suisse/2015/02/26/yves-bouvier-une-ascension-fulgurante-monde-art|publisher=LE TEMPS SA|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> by creating \"artistic hubs\" grouped into [[Free economic zone|freeport facilities]] that offer services and rental facilities to art collectors, museums and companies,<ref name=bilan.ch /> expanding into [[Singapore]] in 2010<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prystay|first1=Cris|title=Singapore Bling|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703691804575255551995870746|publisher=THE WALL STREET JOURNAL|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> and [[Luxembourg]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blenkinsop|first1=Philip|title=Luxembourg opens art freeport to lure super-rich|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/17/art-luxembourg-idUSL6N0RI3CI20140917#BoWIRCJtp64ezHY3.97|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> Another facility was planned in [[Shanghai]] for 2017,<ref>{{cite web|title=Natural Le Coultre opens Shanghai artwork facility|url=http://www.scmp.com/article/1741776/natural-le-coultre-opens-shanghai-artwork-facility|work=South China Morning Post|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> though the project has been suspended.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-02-07/geneva-free-ports-king-mulls-art-fight-s-nearly-1-billion-toll|title=What Geneva\u2019s Art King Lost in Battle With Russian Billionaire|last=Miller|first=Hugo|date=7 February 2017|work=Bloomberg|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe freeports have been subject of increased scrutiny by authorities and governments in recent years. For example, a study by the [[European Parliament]]\u2019s think tank described their high security and discretion as a risk for [[tax evasion]] and [[money laundering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/thinktank/en/document.html?reference=EPRS_STU(2018)627114|title=Money laundering and tax evasion risks in free ports - Think Tank|website=www.europarl.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> A [[European Commission]] report also concluded that these facilities \"could be abused for trade of [[counterfeit]]ed goods, money laundering and other crime if no sufficient checks are carried out to identify the owners of companies using them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-banks-moneylaundering-idUSKCN1UJ1DP|title=EU urges reforms against multi-billion-euro flow of dirty money|date=2019-07-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-10-07|language=en}}</ref> Furthermore, a 2016 [[UNESCO]] report detailed the possibility that freeports can be used by art dealers to trade stolen, [[Looting|looted]] or illegally excavated objects, even many years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/CLT/pdf/2_FC_free_port_working_document_Final_EN_revclean.pdf|title=Free Ports and risks of illicit trafficking of cultural property|last=|first=|date=July 2016|website=UNESCO.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The facilities have been alleged to be a point of sale for expensive art, for example, to museums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latribune.fr/opinions/tribunes/le-marche-de-l-art-en-quete-de-transparence-840950.html|title=Le march\u00e9 de l'art en qu\u00eate de transparence|website=La Tribune|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===== Geneva Freeport =====\n{{Main|Geneva Freeport}}\nThe oldest freeport facility, the [[Federal Council (Switzerland)|Swiss government]] holds the majority stake of 85 percent with Bouvier holding a 5 percent stake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icomturkey.org/en/content/beleaguered-yves-bouvier-defends-himself-and-freeport-system|title=Beleaguered Yves Bouvier defends himself and freeport system {{!}} International Council of Museums Turkey|website=icomturkey.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Bouvier sold his majority participation in 2017, after the Swiss government passed stricter oversight rules over [[customs]] [[warehouse]]s.<ref name=\":9\" /> According to media reports, the freeport has been linked to the trafficking of looted artifacts from [[Syria]], and is regarded as a risk for [[Money laundering|money-laundering]] and [[Tax evasion|tax-evasion]] operations by the [[European Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/treasures-worth-billions-hidden-free-ports-fund-isis-532597|title=Treasures 'hidden' in free ports at risk of funding terror|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/eu-puts-urgent-phasing-out-of-freeports-top-of-agenda|title=European Parliament puts 'urgent' phasing out of freeports top of agenda|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===== Singapore Freeport =====\n{{Main|Singapore Freeport}}\nBouvier built a subsidiary to the Geneva freeport in Singapore in 2010, after the idea was floated with the [[Government of Singapore|Singaporean government]] as early as 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://magazin.lufthansa.com/xx/en/aviation-en/singapur-reichtum-hinter-gittern/|title=Reichtum hinter Gittern|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The facilities host primarily works of art, but [[vintage car]]s, [[wine]],\u00a0[[Jewellery|jewelry]], and [[gold bar]]s of [[Deutsche Bank]] until July 2019, when the bank ceased its usage of the facility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/asias-fort-knox-said-to-be-up-for-sale|title=Asia\u2019s \u2018Fort Knox\u2019, Le Freeport in Singapore, said to be up for sale|last=hermes|date=2019-07-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Unlike in Geneva\u2019s freeport, in which Bouvier is a minority stakeholder, he holds a majority stake in the Singapore facility, describing the idea of the facility a \"great success.\"<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-17/asia-s-fort-knox-said-to-be-up-for-sale-as-owner-fights-tycoon|title=Asia\u2019s \u2018Fort Knox\u2019 Said to Be Up For Sale As Owner Fights Tycoon|last=|first=|date=17 July 2019|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, the Singapore freeport has been for sale since 2017 but a buyer is yet to be found.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n===== Luxembourg Freeport =====\n{{Main|Luxembourg Freeport}}\nThe freeport was inaugurated on 17 September 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gouvernement.lu/fr/gouvernement/etienne-schneider/actualites.html|title=Actualit\u00e9s|website=gouvernement.lu|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> It has been under criticism from the EU since 2018, when it was found to be an enabler for tax evasion by two MEPs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lequotidien.lu/economie/freeport-luxembourg-les-questions-qui-derangent/|title=Freeport Luxembourg: les questions qui d\u00e9rangent|last=Grasser|first=Fabien|website=Le Quotidien|language=fr-FR|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> German MEP [[Wolf Klinz]] in 2019 demanded the freeport be closed for its alleged role in facilitating money laundering and tax evasion.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/european-commission-president-jean-claude-juncker-must-close-tax-loopholes-at-luxembourg-freeport-mep-says|title=European Commission president Jean-Claude Juncker must close tax loopholes at Luxembourg freeport, MEP says|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===Other contributions===\nIn 2004 Bouvier founded the company Art Culture Studio that organizes cultural events, restores furniture, and provides support to the Renaissance Foundation for [[Russia]]n Country Homes, a [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit organization]] that supports research on the restoration of cultural and historic buildings in rural areas. Art Culture Studio helped renovate the 18th century furniture for the [[boudoir]] of [[Empress Jos\u00e9phine|Empress Josephine]] in 2012.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books/about/Natural_Le_Coultre.html?id=GKtKngEACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Natural Le Coultre: un nom qui parcourt le monde|date=2013|publisher=Natural Le Coultre|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe initiated and chaired the [[Moscow]] World Fine Art Fair in 2004, a yearly exhibition taking place in May for art dealers and collectors.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://europaregina.eu/international_art_fairs_antiques_fairs/moscow_world_fine_art_fair-2008-12292007.htm|title=The Moscow World Fine Art Fair - International fine art and antiques fair in the Manege Moscow, Russia|website=europaregina.eu|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> He also contributed to the establishment of the [[Salzburg]] World Fine Art Fair.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://artdaily.com/news/21038/Salzburg-World-Fine-Art-Fair-To-Open-July-27|title=Salzburg World Fine Art Fair To Open July 27|publisher=artdaily|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bouvier initiated the creation of the Singapore [[Pinacoth\u00e8que de Paris|Pinacoth\u00e8que]] de Paris, an expansion of [[Pinacoth\u00e8que de Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/arts/article/2015/06/04/singapour-a-desormais-sa-pinacotheque-de-paris_4647357_1655012.html|title=Singapour a d\u00e9sormais sa Pinacoth\u00e8que de Paris|last1=de Changy|first1=Florence|work=Le Monde|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> The museum was closed in 2016 without explanation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/arts/sudden-closure-of-singapore-pinacotheque-museum-disappoints-art-lovers-frustrates|title=Sudden closure of Singapore Pinacotheque museum disappoints art-lovers, frustrates tenants|last=hermesauto|date=2016-04-09|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> Art Heritage Singapore, the company behind the project and of which Bouvier was a shareholder, was subsequently sued by media and security companies involved in the project for almost $900,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/arts/firm-behind-singapore-pinacotheque-de-paris-faces-two-more-lawsuits|title=Firm behind Singapore Pinacotheque de Paris faces two more lawsuits|last=hermes|date=2016-04-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\nBouvier was involved with the \"p\u00f4le R4\" project, an artistic \"micro-city\" on the site of a former Renault factory in [[Seguin Island]], Paris. The project, designed by French architect [[Jean Nouvel]], was until September 2016 managed and financed by Bouvier, and was scheduled to open in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/10/arts/10iht-rcartoff.html|title=A New Concept in Handling Art|last1=Lankarani|first1=Nazanin|work=The New York Times|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> In September 2016 it was announced that Bouvier had sold his entire stake to the Emerige Group and its financial partner, [[Addax]] and [[Oryx]] Group Limited (AOG).<ref name=\"news.artnet.com\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/paris-r4-new-financial-backer-648308|title=Paris' R4 Finds New Financial Backer \u2013 artnet News|publisher=news.artnet.com|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"24heures\">{{cite web|url=http://www.24heures.ch/economie/yves-bouvier-abandonne-projet-parisien-r4/story/10362656|title=Transaction: Yves Bouvier abandonne le projet parisien R4 \u2013 \u00c9conomie \u2013 24heures.ch|publisher=24heures.ch|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> Artnet noted that the transaction frees the project from its association from Bouvier.<ref name=\"news.artnet.com\" />\n\n==Lawsuits==\n\n===Dispute with Dmitry Rybolovlev===\nIn 2015, Russian billionaire [[Dmitry Rybolovlev]] accused Yves Bouvier of defrauding him out of nearly $1 billion via the sale of artwork at inflated prices while he was employed as a consultant and was receiving a commission of 2 percent on the value of each purchase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/03/13/art-scandal-threatens-to-expose-mass-fraud-in-global-art-market.html|title=Art scandal threatens to expose mass fraud in global art market|last1=Frank|first1=Robert|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/monaco/11436640/Swiss-businessman-Yves-Bouvier-arrested-for-art-fraud.html|title=Monaco FC owner Rybolovlev among alleged victims of huge art scam|last1=Mulholland|first1=Rory|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/art-fraudster-was-helped-by-sotheby-s-says-russian-mogul-xmbjr90f6|title=\u2018Art fraudster\u2019 was helped by Sotheby\u2019s, says Russian mogul|last=Arts Correspondent|first=David Sanderson|date=2019-06-27|work=The Times|access-date=2019-10-09|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> The dispute over 38 works of art gave rise to civil and criminal litigation in [[Singapore]], [[Switzerland]], [[France]], [[Monaco]], [[China]] and the [[United States]].\n\nBouvier has denied all accusations and maintained that as an independent art dealer he was free to set his own commission, whereas Rybolovlev\u2019s lawyers claim a commission of 2 percent had been agreed.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2019/08/08/billionaire-dmitry-rybolovlevs-lawsuit-with-art-dealer-yves-bouvier-puts-sothebys-in-crosshairs/|title=Billionaire Dmitry Rybolovlev's Lawsuit With Art Dealer Yves Bouvier Puts Sotheby\u2019s In Crosshairs|last=Rapoza|first=Kenneth|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\nYves Bouvier met Rybolovlev for the first time in 2003, when he came to see him for the occasion of the delivery of the [[Marc Chagall]] painting, ''[[Le Cirque]]''. Tania Rappo, a friend of the Rybolovlev family, organized the purchase of Marc Chagall's ''Le Cirque'' painting for $6 million dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parismatch.com/Actu/Societe/Scandale-a-Monaco-l-enquete-de-Paris-Match-1350719|title=Scandale \u00e0 Monaco : l'enqu\u00eate de Paris Match|last=Match|first=Paris|website=parismatch.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> When the painting arrived at the premises of Natural Le Coultre, located in the free port of Geneva, the canvas did not have a certificate of authenticity guaranteeing that an artwork is an original. Rybolovlev feared he had been scammed, but Bouvier acquired the certificate a few days later and requested Rappo to organize a meeting with the Rybolovlev at their home in [[Cologny]]. Bouvier promised Rappo that he would give her a commission for every work sold to Rybolovlev, for introducing him to the billionaire.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/02/08/the-bouvier-affair|title=The Art-World Insider Who Went Too Far|last=Knight|first=Sam|date=2016-02-01|access-date=2019-10-21|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> Bouvier subsequently acquired several paintings for Rybolovlev, including [[Vincent van Gogh|Vincent Van Gogh]], [[Pablo Picasso]] and [[Amedeo Modigliani]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAccording to [[Forbes]], the Russian learned of the alleged fraud from Sandy Heller, an art adviser who had sold [[Amedeo Modigliani|Modigliani]]'s ''Nude on a blue cushion'' for $93.5&nbsp;million to Bouvier, who then sold it to Ryboolvlev for $118&nbsp;million. This prompted Rybolovlev to file for fraud and money laundering in Monaco.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|last1=Fontevecchia|first1=Agustino|title=Steve Cohen's Modigliani in the Middle of an Art Market War: Billionaire Rybolovlev vs Yves Bouvier|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/afontevecchia/2015/03/12/steve-cohens-modigliani-in-the-middle-of-an-art-market-war-billionaire-rybolovlev-vs-yves-bouvier/|work=Forbes|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg.com\">{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Hugo|last2=Baker|first2=Stephanie|title=The Billionaire, the Dealer, and the $186 Million Rothko|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-27/a-186-million-rothko-pits-russian-tycoon-against-art-merchant|publisher=Bloomberg Business|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> Upon meeting Rybolovlev in Monaco nine days later, Bouvier was arrested.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"bloomberg.com\" />\n\nOn 26 February 2015, Bouvier was arrested in Monaco on suspicion of defrauding Dmitry Rybolovlev.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/arrest-of-swiss-freeport-owner-yves-bouvier-over-art-fraud-ring-rocks-art-world-270540|title=Arrest of Swiss Freeport Owner Yves Bouvier Over Art Fraud Ring Rocks Art World|date=2015-02-27|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bd248468-bde7-11e4-8cf3-00144feab7de|title=Swiss businessman arrested in art market probe|last=O\u2019Murchu|first=Cynthia|date=26 February 2015|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Bouvier was released on a \u20ac10 million bail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/yves-bouvier-indicted-for-defrauding-dmitry-rybolovlev-held-on-eur10-million-bail-272265|title=\u20ac10 Million Bail Set for Yves Bouvier|date=2015-03-02|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2015/09/15/picasso-l-oligarque-l-heritiere-et-le-marchand-d-art_1383266|title=Picasso : l\u2019oligarque, l\u2019h\u00e9riti\u00e8re et le marchand d\u2019art|date=2015-09-15|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> The case is still ongoing. He is accused of fraud as a result of excessive margins on the sale of paintings, such as on Leonardo da Vinci's Salvator Mundi with a margin of \u20ac50 million. Bouvier denied all accusations, argued that he first heard about the complaint was when he was arrested, and that the price of the paintings had been agreed by both parties.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|last1=Allen|first1=Peter|title=Multi-millionaire businessman who stores cars, wine, cigars and art treasures for the rich and famous is arrested in fraud case|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2970732/Multi-millionaire-businessman-Yves-Bouvier-stores-treasures-rich-famous-arrested-fraud-case.html|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=October 2019}} Bouvier also called for an investigation into [[HSBC]]\u2019s provision of a letter to Monaco police that falsely stated that he and a co-defendant in a money laundering case, Tania Rappo, shared an account at the bank. HSBC responded that this was a simple and clerical mistake.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-billionaires-battle-with-art-dealer-draws-in-hsbc-1447971694|title=Russian Billionaire's Battle With Art Dealer Draws in HSBC|last1=Letzing|first1=John|publisher=THE WALL STREET JOURNAL|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Rybolovlev's lawyer Tetiana Bersheda recorded a private conversation at the oligarch's house a few days before the arrest of Bouvier and Rappo. Following a complaint filed by Tania Rappo, Rybolovlev and Bersheda were briefly placed in police custody on 17 November 2015.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/4966e982-8e00-11e5-8be4-3506bf20cc2b.html|title=The Art Market: Feathers fly in Monaco|last1=Adam|first1=Georgina|work=Financial Times|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tdg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tdg.ch/economie/tetiana-bersheda-c-nouvelle-manuvre/story/21809879|title=March\u00e9 de l\u2019art: Tetiana Bersheda: \"C'est une nouvelle man\u0153uvre\" \u2013 \u00c9conomie \u2013 tdg.ch|publisher=tdg.ch|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> On 23 February 2016, Bersheda was also charged by [[Monaco]] court for violation of the privacy of Rappo.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://monacolife.net/?action=show&id=4974|title=Lawyer for ASM owner in court today|author=Ian Brodie|date=23 February 2016|website=Monacolife.net}}</ref> Bersheda maintains that the recording concerned a professional conversation and was therefore authorized by Monegasque law.<ref name=\"tdg\" />\n\nOn 13 March 2015, Singapore's High Court ordered the global freezing of Bouvier's assets,<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore court orders asset freeze on 'Freeport King'|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/13/us-singapore-court-idUSKBN0M90RH20150313|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> but it was reported that the assets were unfrozen in August of that year on the grounds that Rybolovlev's approach constituted an abuse of process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/singapore-unfreezes-yves-bouviers-assets-327141|title=Singapore Court Unfreezes Bouvier's Assets|date=2015-08-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref><ref name=\":8\"/><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fraud-case-art-dealers-assets-unfrozen-by-court|title=Fraud case: Art dealer's assets unfrozen by court|last=hermes|date=2015-08-23|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> The High Court subsequently ordered the Russian to deposit $100 million to guarantee the amount of damages sustained by Bouvier and his companies due to the injunction.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nAfter Rybolovlev had successfully obtained a [[Asset freezing|Mareva injunction]] from Hong Kong's High Court in July 2015, on 4 September, Bouvier had his assets in Hong Kong unfrozen following a consent summons between Bouvier and two companies linked to Rybolovlev.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-crime/article/1855225/swiss-art-dealer-accused-raking-us1b-secret-profits-sales|title=Swiss art dealer's Hong Kong assets unfrozen amid court battle with Russian tycoon who accused him of swindling|date=2015-09-04|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> High Court recorder Jason Pow Wing-nin SC ordered the injunction against art dealer Bouvier and his Hong Kong company Mei Invest Limited to be lifted.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn March 2016, the High Court of Singapore dismissed Bouvier's attempt to suspend the civil suit filed in the territory, but the case was transferred to the Singapore International Commercial Court, which deals specifically with cross-border commercial disputes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/spore-court-to-hear-14b-art-suit|title=Singapore court to hear $1.4b art suit|last=hermes|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> In May 2016, Bouvier's lawyers filed an appeal against the High Court's ruling, arguing the case should be heard in Switzerland rather than Singapore.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-05-31/art-world-s-1-billion-question-was-russian-a-victim-or-savant|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|title=Art's $1 Billion Question: Was Russian a Victim or Savant? \u2013 Bloomberg|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> On 18 April 2017, the Singapore Court of Appeal overturned the High Court's decision, ruling that the case should be heard in Switzerland and ordering the action in Singapore to be stayed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/apex-court-says-no-to-art-dispute-being-heard-here|title=Apex court says no to art dispute being heard here|last=hermes|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2016, following the lead of European authorities, US Federal prosecutors opened an investigation into Bouvier, whom they described as \"one of the art world\u2019s consummate insiders.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/us-launches-fraud-inquiry-into-art-world-s-consummate-insider|title=US launches fraud inquiry into one of the art world's most consummate insider|last=|first=|date=|website=The Independent|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In April 2016, Bouvier entered a new phase of his campaign to clear his name by hiring global PR group, CNC Communications & Network Consulting, part of French giant [[Publicis|Publicis Groupe]].<ref name=\"odwyerpr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.odwyerpr.com/story/public/6800/2016-04-28/dealer-bouvier-affair-gets-pr-help.html|title=Dealer in 'Bouvier Affair' Gets PR Help \u2013 Thu., Apr. 28, 2016|publisher=odwyerpr.com|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, a federal prosecutor in Geneva opened a criminal investigation into Yves Bouvier, accusing him of fraud to the detriment of Dmitry Rybolovlev.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-02-08/bouvier-questioned-by-geneva-prosecutor-over-russian-art-deals|title=Art Dealer Quizzed After Billionaire\u2019s Fraud Complaint|last=|first=|date=8 February 2018|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nRybolovlev also accused auction house [[Sotheby's|Sotheby\u2019s]] of being complicit in Bouvier\u2019s alleged defrauding scheme.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-02/billionaire-rybolovlev-slaps-sotheby-s-with-380-million-lawsuit|title=Billionaire Slaps Sotheby's With $380 Million Lawsuit|last=|first=|date=3 October 2018|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Rybolovlev has alleged that Bouvier originally paid Sotheby\u2019s $80 million for the \u201cSalvator Mundi\u201d of Leonardo da Vinci, but sold it to Rybolovlev for $127 million, a significant mark-up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-21/russian-billionaire-seeks-to-pull-sotheby-s-into-art-world-fight|title=Russian Billionaire Seeks to Pull Sotheby's Into Art-World Fight|last=|first=|date=21 December 2017|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Russian subsequently accused Sotheby\u2019s of having knowingly and willingly assisted in the fraud.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nIn June 2019 the US District Court for the Southern District of New York ordered that email exchanges between Bouvier and Sotheby\u2019s vice chairman of worldwide private sales Samuel Valette which were previously confidential due to Sotheby\u2019s motion to seal certain documents must be submitted to the court.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/sotheby-s-denied-dismissal-of-rybolovlev-s-usd380m-lawsuit-by-new-york-judge|title=Sotheby's denied dismissal of Rybolovlev's $380m lawsuit by New York judge|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Sotheby\u2019s was involved in the sale of 14 of the works in question.\n\nThe documents detailing correspondence between Bouvier and Sotheby\u2019s staff subsequently filed to the courts \"reveal that Bouvier paid Sotheby\u2019s $83 million for the work, suggesting a 53.62 percent markup as Rybolovlev had alleged.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> According to the files, the process involved a request from Yves Bouvier for Valette to send an evaluation approved by Sotheby's which was to be transferred to Rybolovlev, indicating that Bouvier and Valette apparently coordinated on the value of the appraisals which Bouvier then sent to his client.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.art-critique.com/en/2020/02/the-emperor-has-no-clothes-the-scams-and-swindles-driving-up-art-prices/|title=The emperor has no clothes: the scams and swindles driving up art prices|last=Critique|first=Art|date=2020-02-14|website=Art Critique|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> Bouvier subsequently purchased paintings - via Sotheby's - for amounts lower than those indicated in the valuation, before reselling them to Rybolovlev, mostly at prices higher than those indicated in the evaluation of the auction house. The transaction history that Sotheby's has provided for certain works omits sales to Bouvier, although Valette has personally been involved in many of these sales.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nBoth Bouvier and Sotheby\u2019s have denied any wrongdoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsy.net/news/artsy-editorial-sothebys-will-face-russian-billionaires-380-million-lawsuit-judge-rejected-dismissal-request|title=Sotheby\u2019s to Face $380-Million Lawsuit from Russian Billionaire in Alleged Overcharging Scheme|date=2019-06-26|website=Artsy|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/25/sothebys-must-face-russian-billionaires-lawsuit-over-art-fraud-us-judge|title=Sotheby's must face Russian billionaire's lawsuit over art fraud - U.S. judge|date=2019-06-25|website=euronews|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> In November 2018, Rybolovlev was charged in relation to a probe into influence peddling and corruption by prosecutors in Monaco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-06/russian-billionaire-rybolovlev-questioned-by-police-in-monaco|title=Billionaire Rybolovlev Charged in Monaco Corruption Probe|last=|first=|date=6 November 2018|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Other cases ===\nBouvier was connected to a legal case involving a Canadian collector named Lorette Shefner in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsjournal.com/realcleararts/2015/03/bouvier-shenanigans-chapter-two-steve-cohen.html|title=Bouvier Shenanigans, Chapter Two: Steve Cohen|last=Dobrzynski|first=Judith H.|date=2015-03-16|website=Real Clear Arts|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> Shefner's family claims that she was the victim of a complex fraud, whereby she was persuaded to sell a [[Chaim Soutine|Soutine]] painting at a price far below market value, only to see the work later sold to the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington DC]] for a much higher price.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsjournal.com/realcleararts/2015/03/bouvier-shenanigans-chapter-two-steve-cohen.html|title=Bouvier Shenanigans, Chapter Two: Steve Cohen|website=Real Clear Arts|accessdate=8 January 2016}} A 2013 law suit filed by the Shefner family in New York named Bouvier as a co-defendant with Paris-based Galerie Jacques de la B\u00e9raudi\u00e8re. Bouvier denies the claims against him, arguing that it is circumstantial and not based on any solid evidence. His lawyers have argued that there is no case to answer. The case remains pending.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cases.justia.com/new-york/other-courts/2013-ny-slip-op-32934-u.pdf?ts=1385072189|title=Shefner v Jacques de la Beraudiere|website=Cases.justia.com|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> According to New York court papers from 2013, Bouvier was accused of having conspired \"to disguise the true ownership\" of pieces of art to defraud the Shefner estate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cases.justia.com/new-york/other-courts/2013-ny-slip-op-32934-u.pdf?ts=1385072189|title=Shefner v Jacques de la Beraudiere|last=|first=|date=|website=Justicia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn a separate incident, Bouvier's purported connections to Galerie Jacques de la B\u00e9raudi\u00e8re and his ownership of an off-shore entity called Diva Fine Arts led him to be connected to the case of [[Wolfgang Beltracchi]], a German [[Art forgery|forger]] convicted in 2011 of defrauding a number of collectors, including [[Daniel Filipacchi]], of millions of dollars.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/the-7-million-fake-forgery-scandal-embarrasses-international-art-world-a-768195-2.html|title=The $7 Million Fake: Forgery Scandal Embarrasses International Art World|last=R\u00f6bel|first=Sven|date=13 June 2011|newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]]|accessdate=8 January 2016|last2=Sontheimer|first2=Michael}}</ref> Bouvier has denied any connection to Beltracchi and dismissed media coverage as uninformed speculation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeit.de/2013/18/kunstmarkt-steueroase-yves-bouvier|title=Steueroase: Freih\u00e4fen seien keine Schmuggler-H\u00f6hlen, beteuert Bouvier|website=Die Zeit|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2012, the [[Beijing]] office of one of Bouvier\u2019s subsidiary firms, art transporter IFAS, was raided by local tax authorities, leading to the arrest of several employees, including the general manager Nils Jennrich.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/politik/international/justizdrama-in-china-wann-hoert-der-wahnsinn-auf/7790370.html|title=Justizdrama in China: \"Wann h\u00f6rt der Wahnsinn auf?\"|website=www.handelsblatt.com|language=de|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Through his lawyer, Bouvier contested having affiliation with the company. With the efforts of German diplomats, Jennrich was released and returned to [[Germany]] in 2013, and the case was closed as well as the charges dropped.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/german-citizen-at-the-mercy-of-chinese-justice/a-16088273|title=German citizen at the mercy of Chinese justice {{!}} DW {{!}} 11.07.2012|last=Deutsche Welle|first=|date=|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/17/arts/design/art-world-unnerved-by-chinas-detention-of-two.html|title=Art World Unnerved by China\u2019s Detention of Two|last=Jacobs|first=Andrew|date=2012-07-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-25|last2=Pennington|first2=Clare|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September 2015, Bouvier was indicted on charges of concealed theft of two [[Picasso]]s belonging to Catherine Hutin-Blay, step-daughter of Picasso, who claims that they were stolen from her collection. However, Bouvier demonstrated she received the amount of 8&nbsp;million euros through a [[Liechtenstein]]er trust for their sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/arts/article/2015/09/15/l-homme-d-affaires-yves-bouvier-mis-en-examen-pour-recel-de-deux-picasso-voles_4757968_1655012.html|title=L\u2019homme d\u2019affaires Yves Bouvier mis en examen pour recel de deux Picasso vol\u00e9s|last1=Bellet|first1=Harry|work=Le Monde|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> The prosecution of Liechtenstein closed the case on 1 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tdg.ch/economie/Vaduz-classe-une-plainte-pour-blanchiment-visant-Yves-Bouvier/story/29735335|title=Vaduz classe une plainte pour blanchiment visant Yves Bouvier|author=Pierre-Alexandre Sallier|date=18 December 2015|website=Tdg.ch|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nBouvier and an associate, Marc Francelet, were also allegedly involved in helping former [[president of Angola]], [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos|Jose Eduardo dos Santos]], funnel [[Angola|Angolan]] state funds out of the country.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.africanexponent.com/post/7026-the-west-is-still-helping-corrupt-african-elites-stash-funds-abroad|title=The West is still Helping Corrupt African Elites Stash Funds Abroad {{!}} The African Exponent.|last=Author|first=Guest|website=The African Exponent|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> According to Angolan press reports and French court documents, Bouvier and Francelet used two [[Shell corporation|shell companies]], Brave Ventures Pte Ltd and Francelet Consulting, to make the state funds disappear.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voiceofangola.com/2018/07/20/membros-da-elite-corrupta-angolana-os-chamados-colecionadores-de-arte-pergunte-ao-yves-bouvier-negociante-de-arte-infame/|title=Membros da Elite corrupta Angolana \u2013 os chamados colecionadores de arte? Pergunte ao Yves Bouvier, negociante de arte infame|last=voiceofangola|date=2018-07-20|website=VOICE OF ANGOLA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> \n\n==== Panama Papers ====\nIn the 2015 [[Panama Papers|leak]], it was revealed that Bouvier had at least five off-shore companies linked to him. A lawyer for Bouvier stated these are used for well-established legal purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.occrp.org/en/panamapapers/the-art-of-secrecy/|title=The Art of Secrecy - The Panama Papers|last=Bernstein|first=Jake|website=OCCRP|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==== Alleged tax evasion ====\nIn 2017, the Swiss Federal Tax Administration (FTA) initiated an investigation into Bouvier for tax evasion to the tune of CHF 165 million ($145 million) stemming mostly from income received through art deals with Rybolovlev and proceeds from companies in [[Hong Kong]] and the [[Virgin Islands]] that are allegedly tied to him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/yves-bouvier-swiss-tax-charges-1072205|title=Swiss Authorities Investigate 'Freeport King' Yves Bouvier for More Than $100 Million in Back Taxes|date=2017-09-06|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> In June 2019, the FTA was granted access to documents seized during office raids, following Bouvier\u2019s attempt of blocking them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gothamcity.ch/2019/07/01/affaire-bouvier-le-tpf-doit-revoir-sa-copie-sur-la-levee-des-scelles/|title=Affaire Bouvier: le TPF doit revoir sa copie sur la lev\u00e9e des scell\u00e9s|date=2019-07-01|website=Gotham City|language=fr-FR|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rts.ch/info/economie/10228052-yves-bouvier-gagne-une-manche-face-au-fisc-et-defie-dmitri-rybolovlev.html|title=Yves Bouvier gagne une manche face au fisc et d\u00e9fie Dmitri Rybolovlev|date=2019-02-18|website=rts.ch|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018 the Geneva Prosecutor opened a new criminal investigation into Bouvier relating to an indictment on charges of fraud.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n==== Scherbakov case ====\nIn 2018, another Russian businessman, who according to artnet news emerged to be Vladimir Shcherbakov filed a lawsuit against Yves Bouvier and his associate Thierry Hobaica, who according to media reports Bouvier had engaged to deal with Scherbakov.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/geneva-russian-billionaire-legal-art-advisor-1314749|title=Another Russian Billionaire Is Suing His Swiss Art Dealer for Allegedly Inflating Prices and Pocketing the Extra|date=2018-07-09|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> The Russian accused them of overcharging him in the purchase of 40 artworks, which were allegedly acquired through offshore firms owned by Bouvier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californiatoday.net/2018/07/11/russian-car-czar-vladimir-scherbakov-is-the-collector-who-has-accused-a-swiss-dealer-of-overcharging-him-sources-say/|title=Russian car czar Vladimir Scherbakov is the collector who has accused a Swiss dealer of overcharging him, sources say|last=admin|date=2018-07-11|website=californiatoday|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/2017/04/escroqueries-a-loeuvre-dart-laffaire-bouvier-rebondit-165450|title=Escroqueries \u00e0 l\u2019oeuvre d\u2019art : l\u2019affaire Bouvier rebondit|date=2017-04-22|website=Les Echos|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBouvier is a non-practicing [[Protestantism|Protestant]], and is passionate about [[sailing]] boats \u201cof all kinds\u201d, as well as competition [[horses]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.fr/actualites/articles/dmitry-rybolovlev-contre-yves-bouvier-le-piege-de-loligarque/27575|title=Oligarque contre marchand d'art : r\u00e9v\u00e9lations sur l'affaire qui faut trembler Monaco et la Suisse|last=Gattegno|first=Herv\u00e9|last2=France|first2=Cond\u00e9 Nast Digital|date=2016-02-23|website=Vanity Fair|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\nHe settled in Singapore in 2008 where he currently resides, which is being contested by Swiss tax authorities saying he is still a Geneva resident.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/02/08/the-bouvier-affair|title=The Art-World Insider Who Went Too Far|last=Knight|first=Sam|date=2016-02-01|access-date=2019-10-25|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\nAccording to French magazine ''[[Le Point]]'', Yves Bouvier had allegedly been the patron of [[Zahia Dehar]], a model and designer who had previously worked as a call girl.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lepoint.fr/justice/exclusif-zahia-accusee-de-faux-temoignage-dans-l-affaire-des-footballeurs-22-05-2015-1930461_2386.php|title=Exclusif. Zahia accus\u00e9e de faux t\u00e9moignage dans l'affaire des \"footballeurs\"|last=Labb\u00e9|first=M\u00e9lanie Delattre, Christophe|date=2015-05-22|website=Le Point|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> According to report, Bouvier allegedly organized dinners for his clients, with Dehar as the \"guest star,\" while she was allegedly underage.<ref name=\":13\" /> She became known to the general public after being \"offered\" at the age of 17 as a birthday present to French footballer Frank Rib\u00e9ry. The relationship between Yves Bouvier and Zahia Dehar caught the attention of the French press, but has been denied by both Bouvier and Dehar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/france/point-de-vue/20150902/282754880527718|title=Zahia Dehar Courtisane 2.0|last=Sommelet|first=Pauline|date=2 September 2015|website=Point de vue|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parismatch.com/People/Zahia-sa-nouvelle-vie-sur-grand-ecran-1644393|title=Zahia : sa nouvelle vie sur grand \u00e9cran|last=Match|first=Paris|website=parismatch.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> A former escort colleague of Zahia, known as Sarah, claims that she and Zahia were part of an international pimping ring headed by Yves Bouvier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/societe/justice/proces-zahia-abou-l-homme-assoiffe-de-notoriete-derriere-le-scandale_1314932.html|title=Proc\u00e8s Zahia: Abou, l'homme assoiff\u00e9 de notori\u00e9t\u00e9 derri\u00e8re le scandale|date=2014-01-20|website=LExpress.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtl.fr/actu/justice-faits-divers/un-temoignage-relance-l-affaire-zahia-7800147061|title=Un t\u00e9moignage relance l'affaire Zahia|website=RTL.fr|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/lifestyle-fashion/stylenews/mademoiselle-zahia-takes-london-1230977.html|title=Mademoiselle Zahia takes London|last=March 2020|first=2|website=www.femalefirst.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bouvier, Yves}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss art dealers]]\n[[Category:Swiss businesspeople]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:People from Geneva]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swiss businessman and art dealer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{POV check|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = File:Yves Bouvier.jpg\n| image_size   =\n| name         = Yves Bouvier\n| caption      = Yves Bouvier\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=y|1963|09|08}}\n| birth_place  = Geneva, Switzerland\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| death_cause  =\n| restingplace =\n| nationality  = Swiss\n| religion     = \n| ethnicity    = \n| residence    = Singapore\n| education    =\n| alma mater   = \n| occupation   = CEO, Natural Le Coultre\n| known for    = Businessman and art dealer\n| salary       = \n| networth     = \n| spouse       = \n| parents      = Jean-Jacques Bouvier\n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Yves Bouvier''' (born 8 September 1963 in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Bouvier Affair: A True Story|last=Bregman|first=Alexandra|publisher=Ingram|year=2019|isbn=1733834575|location=|pages=48}}</ref>) is a Swiss businessman and [[art dealer]] best known for his role in [[the Bouvier Affair]] that resulted in criminal charges being brought against him in France and Monaco. He was the president of Natural Le Coultre, an international company specialized in the transportation, storage, scientific analysis, and conservation of works of art, luxurious goods and other collectibles.\n\nIn September 2017, it emerged that Bouvier is under criminal investigation by Swiss authorities amid allegations that he may have evaded more than 100 million euros in taxes related to his cross-border art dealings.<ref>https://news.artnet.com/art-world/yves-bouvier-swiss-tax-charges-1072205</ref> In February 2018, meanwhile, the Geneva Prosecutor reportedly opened a new criminal investigation into Bouvier relating to an indictment on charges of fraud.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n==Early life==\nYves Bouvier is the son of Jean-Jacques Bouvier, owner of Natural Le Coultre, a 150-year-old company specialized in moving and storing goods. Yves Bouvier early developed an interest in art, and dropped out of college to join his father's company in the eighties.<ref name=fr.worldtempus.com>{{cite web|title=Natural Le Coultre, le transport au sommet de son art depuis 150 ans|url=http://fr.worldtempus.com/article/culture/publiart-natural-coultre-transport-au-sommet-son-art-150-ans-326553|publisher=WorldTempus|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\n\n===Natural Le Coultre===\nNatural Transports was formed in 1859 as a moving and furniture storage company. It later became Natural Le Coultre<ref name=fr.worldtempus.com /> in 1901, when Albert-Maurice Natural joined Emile-Etienne Le Coultre to create A. Natural, Le Coultre & Cie. The company's office was located in Geneva. The firm was mainly dealing with commodity deliveries, including fruits, equipment and Red Cross parcels during the [[World War I|First World War]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/02/08/the-bouvier-affair|title=The Art-World Insider Who Went Too Far|last=Knight|first=Sam|date=2016-02-01|access-date=2019-10-07|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/swiss-freeport-king-yves-bouvier-sells-art-storage-company-natural-le-coultre|title=Swiss freeport king Yves Bouvier sells art storage company Natural Le Coultre|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, Jean-Jacques Bouvier began an [[apprenticeship]] at Natural Le Coultre S.A. 30 years later in 1983, the Bouvier family acquired Natural Le Coultre.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1989, Jean-Jacques and Yves Bouvier formed Fine Art Transports Natural Le Coultre SA in Geneva, which provided moving and furniture storage services to the local companies. Hoping that Yves would keep leading the family business, Jean-Jacques Bouvier promoted his son to the position of assistant manager in 1995 and then managing director in 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rc.ge.ch/hrcintreport/createReport?rcentId=5750093500000066031025&lang=FR&order=R&rad=Y |title=NATURAL LE COULTRE SA : inscrite le 24 janvier 1946 : Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 anonyme |publisher=Rc.ge.ch |accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> selling the moving and furniture storage activities to a local company to focus the company on storing, moving, and preserving pieces of art.<ref name=\"bilan.ch\">{{cite web|title=Ce visionnaire qui a pari\u00e9 sur l\u2019Asie|url=http://www.bilan.ch/entreprises-les-plus-de-la-redaction/ce-visionnaire-qui-parie-sur-lasie|publisher=TIFFY&CO.|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> Yves Bouvier moved to [[Singapore]] in 2009 where he currently resides.\n\nUnder Bouvier\u2019s control, Natural Le Coultre owned 5 percent of the [[Geneva Freeport|Geneva freeport]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icomturkey.org/en/content/beleaguered-yves-bouvier-defends-himself-and-freeport-system|title=Beleaguered Yves Bouvier defends himself and freeport system {{!}} ICOM Turkey |website=icomturkey.org|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> but the company was sold to Andr\u00e9 Chenue, a [[Paris]]ian shipping firm, in 2017 for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/swiss-freeport-king-yves-bouvier-sells-art-storage-company-natural-le-coultre|title=Swiss freeport king Yves Bouvier sells art storage company Natural Le Coultre|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/27/arts/yves-bouvier-sells-his-geneva-based-art-storage-company.html|title=Yves Bouvier Sells His Geneva-based Art Storage Company|last=Bowley|first=Graham|date=2017-10-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, in line with the investigation into Bouvier\u2019s potential tax-evasion, Federal Tax Administration (FTA) officials temporarily sequestered one of Natural Le Coultre\u2019s buildings in Geneva, worth 4.5 million [[Swiss franc]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.letemps.ch/suisse/fisc-federal-enquete-yves-bouvier|title=Le fisc f\u00e9d\u00e9ral enqu\u00eate sur Yves Bouvier|date=2017-09-04|access-date=2019-10-02|language=fr|issn=1423-3967}}</ref>\n\n===Freeport facilities===\nBouvier exported the freeport concept, and in 2005, expanded his business model abroad<ref>{{cite web|title=Yves Bouvier: une ascension fulgurante dans le monde de l\u2019art|url=http://www.letemps.ch/suisse/2015/02/26/yves-bouvier-une-ascension-fulgurante-monde-art|publisher=LE TEMPS SA|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> by creating \"artistic hubs\" grouped into [[Free economic zone|freeport facilities]] that offer services and rental facilities to art collectors, museums and companies,<ref name=bilan.ch /> expanding into [[Singapore]] in 2010<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prystay|first1=Cris|title=Singapore Bling|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703691804575255551995870746|publisher=THE WALL STREET JOURNAL|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> and [[Luxembourg]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blenkinsop|first1=Philip|title=Luxembourg opens art freeport to lure super-rich|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/17/art-luxembourg-idUSL6N0RI3CI20140917#BoWIRCJtp64ezHY3.97|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> Another facility was planned in [[Shanghai]] for 2017,<ref>{{cite web|title=Natural Le Coultre opens Shanghai artwork facility|url=http://www.scmp.com/article/1741776/natural-le-coultre-opens-shanghai-artwork-facility|work=South China Morning Post|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> though the project has been suspended.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-02-07/geneva-free-ports-king-mulls-art-fight-s-nearly-1-billion-toll|title=What Geneva\u2019s Art King Lost in Battle With Russian Billionaire|last=Miller|first=Hugo|date=7 February 2017|work=Bloomberg|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe freeports have been subject of increased scrutiny by authorities and governments in recent years. For example, a study by the [[European Parliament]]\u2019s think tank described their high security and discretion as a risk for [[tax evasion]] and [[money laundering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/thinktank/en/document.html?reference=EPRS_STU(2018)627114|title=Money laundering and tax evasion risks in free ports - Think Tank|website=www.europarl.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> A [[European Commission]] report also concluded that these facilities \"could be abused for trade of [[counterfeit]]ed goods, money laundering and other crime if no sufficient checks are carried out to identify the owners of companies using them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-banks-moneylaundering-idUSKCN1UJ1DP|title=EU urges reforms against multi-billion-euro flow of dirty money|date=2019-07-24|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-10-07|language=en}}</ref> Furthermore, a 2016 [[UNESCO]] report detailed the possibility that freeports can be used by art dealers to trade stolen, [[Looting|looted]] or illegally excavated objects, even many years later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/CLT/pdf/2_FC_free_port_working_document_Final_EN_revclean.pdf|title=Free Ports and risks of illicit trafficking of cultural property|last=|first=|date=July 2016|website=UNESCO.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The facilities have been alleged to be a point of sale for expensive art, for example, to museums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latribune.fr/opinions/tribunes/le-marche-de-l-art-en-quete-de-transparence-840950.html|title=Le march\u00e9 de l'art en qu\u00eate de transparence|website=La Tribune|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===== Geneva Freeport =====\n{{Main|Geneva Freeport}}\nThe oldest freeport facility, the [[Federal Council (Switzerland)|Swiss government]] holds the majority stake of 85 percent with Bouvier holding a 5 percent stake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://icomturkey.org/en/content/beleaguered-yves-bouvier-defends-himself-and-freeport-system|title=Beleaguered Yves Bouvier defends himself and freeport system {{!}} International Council of Museums Turkey|website=icomturkey.org|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Bouvier sold his majority participation in 2017, after the Swiss government passed stricter oversight rules over [[customs]] [[warehouse]]s.<ref name=\":9\" /> According to media reports, the freeport has been linked to the trafficking of looted artifacts from [[Syria]], and is regarded as a risk for [[Money laundering|money-laundering]] and [[Tax evasion|tax-evasion]] operations by the [[European Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/treasures-worth-billions-hidden-free-ports-fund-isis-532597|title=Treasures 'hidden' in free ports at risk of funding terror|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/eu-puts-urgent-phasing-out-of-freeports-top-of-agenda|title=European Parliament puts 'urgent' phasing out of freeports top of agenda|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===== Singapore Freeport =====\n{{Main|Singapore Freeport}}\nBouvier built a subsidiary to the Geneva freeport in Singapore in 2010, after the idea was floated with the [[Government of Singapore|Singaporean government]] as early as 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://magazin.lufthansa.com/xx/en/aviation-en/singapur-reichtum-hinter-gittern/|title=Reichtum hinter Gittern|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The facilities host primarily works of art, but [[vintage car]]s, [[wine]],\u00a0[[Jewellery|jewelry]], and [[gold bar]]s of [[Deutsche Bank]] until July 2019, when the bank ceased its usage of the facility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/asias-fort-knox-said-to-be-up-for-sale|title=Asia\u2019s \u2018Fort Knox\u2019, Le Freeport in Singapore, said to be up for sale|last=hermes|date=2019-07-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Unlike in Geneva\u2019s freeport, in which Bouvier is a minority stakeholder, he holds a majority stake in the Singapore facility, describing the idea of the facility a \"great success.\"<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-17/asia-s-fort-knox-said-to-be-up-for-sale-as-owner-fights-tycoon|title=Asia\u2019s \u2018Fort Knox\u2019 Said to Be Up For Sale As Owner Fights Tycoon|last=|first=|date=17 July 2019|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, the Singapore freeport has been for sale since 2017 but a buyer is yet to be found.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n===== Luxembourg Freeport =====\n{{Main|Luxembourg Freeport}}\nThe freeport was inaugurated on 17 September 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gouvernement.lu/fr/gouvernement/etienne-schneider/actualites.html|title=Actualit\u00e9s|website=gouvernement.lu|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> It has been under criticism from the EU since 2018, when it was found to be an enabler for tax evasion by two MEPs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lequotidien.lu/economie/freeport-luxembourg-les-questions-qui-derangent/|title=Freeport Luxembourg: les questions qui d\u00e9rangent|last=Grasser|first=Fabien|website=Le Quotidien|language=fr-FR|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> German MEP [[Wolf Klinz]] in 2019 demanded the freeport be closed for its alleged role in facilitating money laundering and tax evasion.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/european-commission-president-jean-claude-juncker-must-close-tax-loopholes-at-luxembourg-freeport-mep-says|title=European Commission president Jean-Claude Juncker must close tax loopholes at Luxembourg freeport, MEP says|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===Other contributions===\nIn 2004 Bouvier founded the company Art Culture Studio that organizes cultural events, restores furniture, and provides support to the Renaissance Foundation for [[Russia]]n Country Homes, a [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit organization]] that supports research on the restoration of cultural and historic buildings in rural areas. Art Culture Studio helped renovate the 18th century furniture for the [[boudoir]] of [[Empress Jos\u00e9phine|Empress Josephine]] in 2012.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books/about/Natural_Le_Coultre.html?id=GKtKngEACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Natural Le Coultre: un nom qui parcourt le monde|date=2013|publisher=Natural Le Coultre|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe initiated and chaired the [[Moscow]] World Fine Art Fair in 2004, a yearly exhibition taking place in May for art dealers and collectors.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://europaregina.eu/international_art_fairs_antiques_fairs/moscow_world_fine_art_fair-2008-12292007.htm|title=The Moscow World Fine Art Fair - International fine art and antiques fair in the Manege Moscow, Russia|website=europaregina.eu|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> He also contributed to the establishment of the [[Salzburg]] World Fine Art Fair.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://artdaily.com/news/21038/Salzburg-World-Fine-Art-Fair-To-Open-July-27|title=Salzburg World Fine Art Fair To Open July 27|publisher=artdaily|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bouvier initiated the creation of the Singapore [[Pinacoth\u00e8que de Paris|Pinacoth\u00e8que]] de Paris, an expansion of [[Pinacoth\u00e8que de Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/arts/article/2015/06/04/singapour-a-desormais-sa-pinacotheque-de-paris_4647357_1655012.html|title=Singapour a d\u00e9sormais sa Pinacoth\u00e8que de Paris|last1=de Changy|first1=Florence|work=Le Monde|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> The museum was closed in 2016 without explanation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/arts/sudden-closure-of-singapore-pinacotheque-museum-disappoints-art-lovers-frustrates|title=Sudden closure of Singapore Pinacotheque museum disappoints art-lovers, frustrates tenants|last=hermesauto|date=2016-04-09|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> Art Heritage Singapore, the company behind the project and of which Bouvier was a shareholder, was subsequently sued by media and security companies involved in the project for almost $900,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/arts/firm-behind-singapore-pinacotheque-de-paris-faces-two-more-lawsuits|title=Firm behind Singapore Pinacotheque de Paris faces two more lawsuits|last=hermes|date=2016-04-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\nBouvier was involved with the \"p\u00f4le R4\" project, an artistic \"micro-city\" on the site of a former Renault factory in [[Seguin Island]], Paris. The project, designed by French architect [[Jean Nouvel]], was until September 2016 managed and financed by Bouvier, and was scheduled to open in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/10/arts/10iht-rcartoff.html|title=A New Concept in Handling Art|last1=Lankarani|first1=Nazanin|work=The New York Times|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> In September 2016 it was announced that Bouvier had sold his entire stake to the Emerige Group and its financial partner, [[Addax]] and [[Oryx]] Group Limited (AOG).<ref name=\"news.artnet.com\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/paris-r4-new-financial-backer-648308|title=Paris' R4 Finds New Financial Backer \u2013 artnet News|publisher=news.artnet.com|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"24heures\">{{cite web|url=http://www.24heures.ch/economie/yves-bouvier-abandonne-projet-parisien-r4/story/10362656|title=Transaction: Yves Bouvier abandonne le projet parisien R4 \u2013 \u00c9conomie \u2013 24heures.ch|publisher=24heures.ch|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> Artnet noted that the transaction frees the project from its association from Bouvier.<ref name=\"news.artnet.com\" />\n\n==Lawsuits==\n\n===Dispute with Dmitry Rybolovlev===\nIn 2015, Russian billionaire [[Dmitry Rybolovlev]] accused Yves Bouvier of defrauding him out of nearly $1 billion via the sale of artwork at inflated prices while he was employed as a consultant and was receiving a commission of 2 percent on the value of each purchase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/03/13/art-scandal-threatens-to-expose-mass-fraud-in-global-art-market.html|title=Art scandal threatens to expose mass fraud in global art market|last1=Frank|first1=Robert|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/monaco/11436640/Swiss-businessman-Yves-Bouvier-arrested-for-art-fraud.html|title=Monaco FC owner Rybolovlev among alleged victims of huge art scam|last1=Mulholland|first1=Rory|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/art-fraudster-was-helped-by-sotheby-s-says-russian-mogul-xmbjr90f6|title=\u2018Art fraudster\u2019 was helped by Sotheby\u2019s, says Russian mogul|last=Arts\u00a0Correspondent|first=David Sanderson|date=2019-06-27|work=The Times|access-date=2019-10-09|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> The dispute over 38 works of art gave rise to civil and criminal litigation in [[Singapore]], [[Switzerland]], [[France]], [[Monaco]], [[China]] and the [[United States]].\n\nBouvier has denied all accusations and maintained that as an independent art dealer he was free to set his own commission, whereas Rybolovlev\u2019s lawyers claim a commission of 2 percent had been agreed.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2019/08/08/billionaire-dmitry-rybolovlevs-lawsuit-with-art-dealer-yves-bouvier-puts-sothebys-in-crosshairs/|title=Billionaire Dmitry Rybolovlev's Lawsuit With Art Dealer Yves Bouvier Puts Sotheby\u2019s In Crosshairs|last=Rapoza|first=Kenneth|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\nYves Bouvier met Rybolovlev for the first time in 2003, when he came to see him for the occasion of the delivery of the [[Marc Chagall]] painting, ''[[Le Cirque]]''. Tania Rappo, a friend of the Rybolovlev family, organized the purchase of Marc Chagall's ''Le Cirque'' painting for $6 million dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parismatch.com/Actu/Societe/Scandale-a-Monaco-l-enquete-de-Paris-Match-1350719|title=Scandale \u00e0 Monaco : l'enqu\u00eate de Paris Match|last=Match|first=Paris|website=parismatch.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> When the painting arrived at the premises of Natural Le Coultre, located in the free port of Geneva, the canvas did not have a certificate of authenticity guaranteeing that an artwork is an original. Rybolovlev feared he had been scammed, but Bouvier acquired the certificate a few days later and requested Rappo to organize a meeting with the Rybolovlev at their home in [[Cologny]]. Bouvier promised Rappo that he would give her a commission for every work sold to Rybolovlev, for introducing him to the billionaire.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/02/08/the-bouvier-affair|title=The Art-World Insider Who Went Too Far|last=Knight|first=Sam|date=2016-02-01|access-date=2019-10-21|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> Bouvier subsequently acquired several paintings for Rybolovlev, including [[Vincent van Gogh|Vincent Van Gogh]], [[Pablo Picasso]] and [[Amedeo Modigliani]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAccording to [[Forbes]], the Russian learned of the alleged fraud from Sandy Heller, an art adviser who had sold [[Amedeo Modigliani|Modigliani]]'s ''Nude on a blue cushion'' for $93.5&nbsp;million to Bouvier, who then sold it to Ryboolvlev for $118&nbsp;million. This prompted Rybolovlev to file for fraud and money laundering in Monaco.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|last1=Fontevecchia|first1=Agustino|title=Steve Cohen's Modigliani in the Middle of an Art Market War: Billionaire Rybolovlev vs Yves Bouvier|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/afontevecchia/2015/03/12/steve-cohens-modigliani-in-the-middle-of-an-art-market-war-billionaire-rybolovlev-vs-yves-bouvier/|work=Forbes|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg.com\">{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Hugo|last2=Baker|first2=Stephanie|title=The Billionaire, the Dealer, and the $186 Million Rothko|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-27/a-186-million-rothko-pits-russian-tycoon-against-art-merchant|publisher=Bloomberg Business|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> Upon meeting Rybolovlev in Monaco nine days later, Bouvier was arrested.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"bloomberg.com\" />\n\nOn 26 February 2015, Bouvier was arrested in Monaco on suspicion of defrauding Dmitry Rybolovlev.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/arrest-of-swiss-freeport-owner-yves-bouvier-over-art-fraud-ring-rocks-art-world-270540|title=Arrest of Swiss Freeport Owner Yves Bouvier Over Art Fraud Ring Rocks Art World|date=2015-02-27|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bd248468-bde7-11e4-8cf3-00144feab7de|title=Swiss businessman arrested in art market probe|last=O\u2019Murchu|first=Cynthia|date=26 February 2015|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Bouvier was released on a \u20ac10 million bail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/yves-bouvier-indicted-for-defrauding-dmitry-rybolovlev-held-on-eur10-million-bail-272265|title=\u20ac10 Million Bail Set for Yves Bouvier|date=2015-03-02|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2015/09/15/picasso-l-oligarque-l-heritiere-et-le-marchand-d-art_1383266|title=Picasso : l\u2019oligarque, l\u2019h\u00e9riti\u00e8re et le marchand d\u2019art|date=2015-09-15|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> The case is still ongoing. He is accused of fraud as a result of excessive margins on the sale of paintings, such as on Leonardo da Vinci's Salvator Mundi with a margin of \u20ac50 million. Bouvier denied all accusations, argued that he first heard about the complaint was when he was arrested, and that the price of the paintings had been agreed by both parties.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|last1=Allen|first1=Peter|title=Multi-millionaire businessman who stores cars, wine, cigars and art treasures for the rich and famous is arrested in fraud case|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2970732/Multi-millionaire-businessman-Yves-Bouvier-stores-treasures-rich-famous-arrested-fraud-case.html|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=October 2019}} Bouvier also called for an investigation into [[HSBC]]\u2019s provision of a letter to Monaco police that falsely stated that he and a co-defendant in a money laundering case, Tania Rappo, shared an account at the bank. HSBC responded that this was a simple and clerical mistake.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-billionaires-battle-with-art-dealer-draws-in-hsbc-1447971694|title=Russian Billionaire's Battle With Art Dealer Draws in HSBC|last1=Letzing|first1=John|publisher=THE WALL STREET JOURNAL|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Rybolovlev's lawyer Tetiana Bersheda recorded a private conversation at the oligarch's house a few days before the arrest of Bouvier and Rappo. Following a complaint filed by Tania Rappo, Rybolovlev and Bersheda were briefly placed in police custody on 17 November 2015.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/4966e982-8e00-11e5-8be4-3506bf20cc2b.html|title=The Art Market: Feathers fly in Monaco|last1=Adam|first1=Georgina|work=Financial Times|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tdg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tdg.ch/economie/tetiana-bersheda-c-nouvelle-manuvre/story/21809879|title=March\u00e9 de l\u2019art: Tetiana Bersheda: \"C'est une nouvelle man\u0153uvre\" \u2013 \u00c9conomie \u2013 tdg.ch|publisher=tdg.ch|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> On 23 February 2016, Bersheda was also charged by [[Monaco]] court for violation of the privacy of Rappo.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://monacolife.net/?action=show&id=4974|title=Lawyer for ASM owner in court today|author=Ian Brodie|date=23 February 2016|website=Monacolife.net}}</ref> Bersheda maintains that the recording concerned a professional conversation and was therefore authorized by Monegasque law.<ref name=\"tdg\" />\n\nOn 13 March 2015, Singapore's High Court ordered the global freezing of Bouvier's assets,<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore court orders asset freeze on 'Freeport King'|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/13/us-singapore-court-idUSKBN0M90RH20150313|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> but it was reported that the assets were unfrozen in August of that year on the grounds that Rybolovlev's approach constituted an abuse of process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/singapore-unfreezes-yves-bouviers-assets-327141|title=Singapore Court Unfreezes Bouvier's Assets|date=2015-08-25|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref><ref name=\":8\"/><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fraud-case-art-dealers-assets-unfrozen-by-court|title=Fraud case: Art dealer's assets unfrozen by court|last=hermes|date=2015-08-23|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> The High Court subsequently ordered the Russian to deposit $100 million to guarantee the amount of damages sustained by Bouvier and his companies due to the injunction.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nAfter Rybolovlev had successfully obtained a [[Asset freezing|Mareva injunction]] from Hong Kong's High Court in July 2015, on 4 September, Bouvier had his assets in Hong Kong unfrozen following a consent summons between Bouvier and two companies linked to Rybolovlev.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-crime/article/1855225/swiss-art-dealer-accused-raking-us1b-secret-profits-sales|title=Swiss art dealer's Hong Kong assets unfrozen amid court battle with Russian tycoon who accused him of swindling|date=2015-09-04|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> High Court recorder Jason Pow Wing-nin SC ordered the injunction against art dealer Bouvier and his Hong Kong company Mei Invest Limited to be lifted.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nIn March 2016, the High Court of Singapore dismissed Bouvier's attempt to suspend the civil suit filed in the territory, but the case was transferred to the Singapore International Commercial Court, which deals specifically with cross-border commercial disputes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/spore-court-to-hear-14b-art-suit|title=Singapore court to hear $1.4b art suit|last=hermes|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> In May 2016, Bouvier's lawyers filed an appeal against the High Court's ruling, arguing the case should be heard in Switzerland rather than Singapore.<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-05-31/art-world-s-1-billion-question-was-russian-a-victim-or-savant|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|title=Art's $1 Billion Question: Was Russian a Victim or Savant? \u2013 Bloomberg|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref> On 18 April 2017, the Singapore Court of Appeal overturned the High Court's decision, ruling that the case should be heard in Switzerland and ordering the action in Singapore to be stayed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/apex-court-says-no-to-art-dispute-being-heard-here|title=Apex court says no to art dispute being heard here|last=hermes|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2016, following the lead of European authorities, US Federal prosecutors opened an investigation into Bouvier, whom they described as \"one of the art world\u2019s consummate insiders.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/us-launches-fraud-inquiry-into-art-world-s-consummate-insider|title=US launches fraud inquiry into one of the art world's most consummate insider|last=|first=|date=|website=The Independent|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In April 2016, Bouvier entered a new phase of his campaign to clear his name by hiring global PR group, CNC Communications & Network Consulting, part of French giant [[Publicis|Publicis Groupe]].<ref name=\"odwyerpr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.odwyerpr.com/story/public/6800/2016-04-28/dealer-bouvier-affair-gets-pr-help.html|title=Dealer in 'Bouvier Affair' Gets PR Help \u2013 Thu., Apr. 28, 2016|publisher=odwyerpr.com|accessdate=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, a federal prosecutor in Geneva opened a criminal investigation into Yves Bouvier, accusing him of fraud to the detriment of Dmitry Rybolovlev.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-02-08/bouvier-questioned-by-geneva-prosecutor-over-russian-art-deals|title=Art Dealer Quizzed After Billionaire\u2019s Fraud Complaint|last=|first=|date=8 February 2018|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nRybolovlev also accused auction house [[Sotheby's|Sotheby\u2019s]] of being complicit in Bouvier\u2019s alleged defrauding scheme.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-02/billionaire-rybolovlev-slaps-sotheby-s-with-380-million-lawsuit|title=Billionaire Slaps Sotheby's With $380 Million Lawsuit|last=|first=|date=3 October 2018|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Rybolovlev has alleged that Bouvier originally paid Sotheby\u2019s $80 million for the \u201cSalvator Mundi\u201d of Leonardo da Vinci, but sold it to Rybolovlev for $127 million, a significant mark-up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-21/russian-billionaire-seeks-to-pull-sotheby-s-into-art-world-fight|title=Russian Billionaire Seeks to Pull Sotheby's Into Art-World Fight|last=|first=|date=21 December 2017|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Russian subsequently accused Sotheby\u2019s of having knowingly and willingly assisted in the fraud.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nIn June 2019 the US District Court for the Southern District of New York ordered that email exchanges between Bouvier and Sotheby\u2019s vice chairman of worldwide private sales Samuel Valette which were previously confidential due to Sotheby\u2019s motion to seal certain documents must be submitted to the court.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/news/sotheby-s-denied-dismissal-of-rybolovlev-s-usd380m-lawsuit-by-new-york-judge|title=Sotheby's denied dismissal of Rybolovlev's $380m lawsuit by New York judge|website=www.theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Sotheby\u2019s was involved in the sale of 14 of the works in question.\n\nThe documents detailing correspondence between Bouvier and Sotheby\u2019s staff subsequently filed to the courts \"reveal that Bouvier paid Sotheby\u2019s $83 million for the work, suggesting a 53.62 percent markup as Rybolovlev had alleged.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> According to the files, the process involved a request from Yves Bouvier for Valette to send an evaluation approved by Sotheby's which was to be transferred to Rybolovlev, indicating that Bouvier and Valette apparently coordinated on the value of the appraisals which Bouvier then sent to his client.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.art-critique.com/en/2020/02/the-emperor-has-no-clothes-the-scams-and-swindles-driving-up-art-prices/|title=The emperor has no clothes: the scams and swindles driving up art prices|last=Critique|first=Art|date=2020-02-14|website=Art Critique|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> Bouvier subsequently purchased paintings - via Sotheby's - for amounts lower than those indicated in the valuation, before reselling them to Rybolovlev, mostly at prices higher than those indicated in the evaluation of the auction house. The transaction history that Sotheby's has provided for certain works omits sales to Bouvier, although Valette has personally been involved in many of these sales.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nBoth Bouvier and Sotheby\u2019s have denied any wrongdoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsy.net/news/artsy-editorial-sothebys-will-face-russian-billionaires-380-million-lawsuit-judge-rejected-dismissal-request|title=Sotheby\u2019s to Face $380-Million Lawsuit from Russian Billionaire in Alleged Overcharging Scheme|date=2019-06-26|website=Artsy|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/25/sothebys-must-face-russian-billionaires-lawsuit-over-art-fraud-us-judge|title=Sotheby's must face Russian billionaire's lawsuit over art fraud - U.S. judge|date=2019-06-25|website=euronews|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> In November 2018, Rybolovlev was charged in relation to a probe into influence peddling and corruption by prosecutors in Monaco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-06/russian-billionaire-rybolovlev-questioned-by-police-in-monaco|title=Billionaire Rybolovlev Charged in Monaco Corruption Probe|last=|first=|date=6 November 2018|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Other cases ===\nBouvier was connected to a legal case involving a Canadian collector named Lorette Shefner in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsjournal.com/realcleararts/2015/03/bouvier-shenanigans-chapter-two-steve-cohen.html|title=Bouvier Shenanigans, Chapter Two: Steve Cohen|last=Dobrzynski|first=Judith H.|date=2015-03-16|website=Real Clear Arts|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> Shefner's family claims that she was the victim of a complex fraud, whereby she was persuaded to sell a [[Chaim Soutine|Soutine]] painting at a price far below market value, only to see the work later sold to the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington DC]] for a much higher price.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsjournal.com/realcleararts/2015/03/bouvier-shenanigans-chapter-two-steve-cohen.html|title=Bouvier Shenanigans, Chapter Two: Steve Cohen|website=Real Clear Arts|accessdate=8 January 2016}} A 2013 law suit filed by the Shefner family in New York named Bouvier as a co-defendant with Paris-based Galerie Jacques de la B\u00e9raudi\u00e8re. Bouvier denies the claims against him, arguing that it is circumstantial and not based on any solid evidence. His lawyers have argued that there is no case to answer. The case remains pending.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cases.justia.com/new-york/other-courts/2013-ny-slip-op-32934-u.pdf?ts=1385072189|title=Shefner v Jacques de la Beraudiere|website=Cases.justia.com|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> According to New York court papers from 2013, Bouvier was accused of having conspired \"to disguise the true ownership\" of pieces of art to defraud the Shefner estate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cases.justia.com/new-york/other-courts/2013-ny-slip-op-32934-u.pdf?ts=1385072189|title=Shefner v Jacques de la Beraudiere|last=|first=|date=|website=Justicia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn a separate incident, Bouvier's purported connections to Galerie Jacques de la B\u00e9raudi\u00e8re and his ownership of an off-shore entity called Diva Fine Arts led him to be connected to the case of [[Wolfgang Beltracchi]], a German [[Art forgery|forger]] convicted in 2011 of defrauding a number of collectors, including [[Daniel Filipacchi]], of millions of dollars.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/the-7-million-fake-forgery-scandal-embarrasses-international-art-world-a-768195-2.html|title=The $7 Million Fake: Forgery Scandal Embarrasses International Art World|last=R\u00f6bel|first=Sven|date=13 June 2011|newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]]|accessdate=8 January 2016|last2=Sontheimer|first2=Michael}}</ref> Bouvier has denied any connection to Beltracchi and dismissed media coverage as uninformed speculation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeit.de/2013/18/kunstmarkt-steueroase-yves-bouvier|title=Steueroase: Freih\u00e4fen seien keine Schmuggler-H\u00f6hlen, beteuert Bouvier|website=Die Zeit|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2012, the [[Beijing]] office of one of Bouvier\u2019s subsidiary firms, art transporter IFAS, was raided by local tax authorities, leading to the arrest of several employees, including the general manager Nils Jennrich.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/politik/international/justizdrama-in-china-wann-hoert-der-wahnsinn-auf/7790370.html|title=Justizdrama in China: \"Wann h\u00f6rt der Wahnsinn auf?\"|website=www.handelsblatt.com|language=de|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> Through his lawyer, Bouvier contested having affiliation with the company. With the efforts of German diplomats, Jennrich was released and returned to [[Germany]] in 2013, and the case was closed as well as the charges dropped.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/german-citizen-at-the-mercy-of-chinese-justice/a-16088273|title=German citizen at the mercy of Chinese justice {{!}} DW {{!}} 11.07.2012|last=Deutsche Welle|first=|date=|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/17/arts/design/art-world-unnerved-by-chinas-detention-of-two.html|title=Art World Unnerved by China\u2019s Detention of Two|last=Jacobs|first=Andrew|date=2012-07-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-25|last2=Pennington|first2=Clare|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September 2015, Bouvier was indicted on charges of concealed theft of two [[Picasso]]s belonging to Catherine Hutin-Blay, step-daughter of Picasso, who claims that they were stolen from her collection. However, Bouvier demonstrated she received the amount of 8&nbsp;million euros through a [[Liechtenstein]]er trust for their sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/arts/article/2015/09/15/l-homme-d-affaires-yves-bouvier-mis-en-examen-pour-recel-de-deux-picasso-voles_4757968_1655012.html|title=L\u2019homme d\u2019affaires Yves Bouvier mis en examen pour recel de deux Picasso vol\u00e9s|last1=Bellet|first1=Harry|work=Le Monde|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref> The prosecution of Liechtenstein closed the case on 1 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tdg.ch/economie/Vaduz-classe-une-plainte-pour-blanchiment-visant-Yves-Bouvier/story/29735335|title=Vaduz classe une plainte pour blanchiment visant Yves Bouvier|author=Pierre-Alexandre Sallier|date=18 December 2015|website=Tdg.ch|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nBouvier and an associate, Marc Francelet, were also allegedly involved in helping former [[president of Angola]], [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos|Jose Eduardo dos Santos]], funnel [[Angola|Angolan]] state funds out of the country.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.africanexponent.com/post/7026-the-west-is-still-helping-corrupt-african-elites-stash-funds-abroad|title=The West is still Helping Corrupt African Elites Stash Funds Abroad {{!}} The African Exponent.|last=Author|first=Guest|website=The African Exponent|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> According to Angolan press reports and French court documents, Bouvier and Francelet used two [[Shell corporation|shell companies]], Brave Ventures Pte Ltd and Francelet Consulting, to make the state funds disappear.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voiceofangola.com/2018/07/20/membros-da-elite-corrupta-angolana-os-chamados-colecionadores-de-arte-pergunte-ao-yves-bouvier-negociante-de-arte-infame/|title=Membros da Elite corrupta Angolana \u2013 os chamados colecionadores de arte? Pergunte ao Yves Bouvier, negociante de arte infame|last=voiceofangola|date=2018-07-20|website=VOICE OF ANGOLA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> \n\n==== Panama Papers ====\nIn the 2015 [[Panama Papers|leak]], it was revealed that Bouvier had at least five off-shore companies linked to him. A lawyer for Bouvier stated these are used for well-established legal purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.occrp.org/en/panamapapers/the-art-of-secrecy/|title=The Art of Secrecy - The Panama Papers|last=Bernstein|first=Jake|website=OCCRP|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==== Alleged tax evasion ====\nIn 2017, the Swiss Federal Tax Administration (FTA) initiated an investigation into Bouvier for tax evasion to the tune of CHF 165 million ($145 million) stemming mostly from income received through art deals with Rybolovlev and proceeds from companies in [[Hong Kong]] and the [[Virgin Islands]] that are allegedly tied to him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/yves-bouvier-swiss-tax-charges-1072205|title=Swiss Authorities Investigate 'Freeport King' Yves Bouvier for More Than $100 Million in Back Taxes|date=2017-09-06|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> In June 2019, the FTA was granted access to documents seized during office raids, following Bouvier\u2019s attempt of blocking them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gothamcity.ch/2019/07/01/affaire-bouvier-le-tpf-doit-revoir-sa-copie-sur-la-levee-des-scelles/|title=Affaire Bouvier: le TPF doit revoir sa copie sur la lev\u00e9e des scell\u00e9s|date=2019-07-01|website=Gotham City|language=fr-FR|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rts.ch/info/economie/10228052-yves-bouvier-gagne-une-manche-face-au-fisc-et-defie-dmitri-rybolovlev.html|title=Yves Bouvier gagne une manche face au fisc et d\u00e9fie Dmitri Rybolovlev|date=2019-02-18|website=rts.ch|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018 the Geneva Prosecutor opened a new criminal investigation into Bouvier relating to an indictment on charges of fraud.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n==== Scherbakov case ====\nIn 2018, another Russian businessman, who according to artnet news emerged to be Vladimir Shcherbakov filed a lawsuit against Yves Bouvier and his associate Thierry Hobaica, who according to media reports Bouvier had engaged to deal with Scherbakov.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/geneva-russian-billionaire-legal-art-advisor-1314749|title=Another Russian Billionaire Is Suing His Swiss Art Dealer for Allegedly Inflating Prices and Pocketing the Extra|date=2018-07-09|website=artnet News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> The Russian accused them of overcharging him in the purchase of 40 artworks, which were allegedly acquired through offshore firms owned by Bouvier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://californiatoday.net/2018/07/11/russian-car-czar-vladimir-scherbakov-is-the-collector-who-has-accused-a-swiss-dealer-of-overcharging-him-sources-say/|title=Russian car czar Vladimir Scherbakov is the collector who has accused a Swiss dealer of overcharging him, sources say|last=admin|date=2018-07-11|website=californiatoday|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/2017/04/escroqueries-a-loeuvre-dart-laffaire-bouvier-rebondit-165450|title=Escroqueries \u00e0 l\u2019oeuvre d\u2019art : l\u2019affaire Bouvier rebondit|date=2017-04-22|website=Les Echos|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBouvier is a non-practicing [[Protestantism|Protestant]], and is passionate about [[sailing]] boats \u201cof all kinds\u201d, as well as competition [[horses]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.fr/actualites/articles/dmitry-rybolovlev-contre-yves-bouvier-le-piege-de-loligarque/27575|title=Oligarque contre marchand d'art : r\u00e9v\u00e9lations sur l'affaire qui faut trembler Monaco et la Suisse|last=Gattegno|first=Herv\u00e9|last2=France|first2=Cond\u00e9 Nast Digital|date=2016-02-23|website=Vanity Fair|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\nHe settled in Singapore in 2008 where he currently resides, which is being contested by Swiss tax authorities saying he is still a Geneva resident.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/02/08/the-bouvier-affair|title=The Art-World Insider Who Went Too Far|last=Knight|first=Sam|date=2016-02-01|access-date=2019-10-25|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\nAccording to French magazine ''[[Le Point]]'', Yves Bouvier had allegedly been the patron of [[Zahia Dehar]], a model and designer who had previously worked as a call girl.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lepoint.fr/justice/exclusif-zahia-accusee-de-faux-temoignage-dans-l-affaire-des-footballeurs-22-05-2015-1930461_2386.php|title=Exclusif. Zahia accus\u00e9e de faux t\u00e9moignage dans l'affaire des \"footballeurs\"|last=Labb\u00e9|first=M\u00e9lanie Delattre, Christophe|date=2015-05-22|website=Le Point|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> According to report, Bouvier allegedly organized dinners for his clients, with Dehar as the \"guest star,\" while she was allegedly underage.<ref name=\":13\" /> She became known to the general public after being \"offered\" at the age of 17 as a birthday present to French footballer Frank Rib\u00e9ry. The relationship between Yves Bouvier and Zahia Dehar caught the attention of the French press, but has been denied by both Bouvier and Dehar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/france/point-de-vue/20150902/282754880527718|title=Zahia Dehar Courtisane 2.0|last=Sommelet|first=Pauline|date=2 September 2015|website=Point de vue|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parismatch.com/People/Zahia-sa-nouvelle-vie-sur-grand-ecran-1644393|title=Zahia : sa nouvelle vie sur grand \u00e9cran|last=Match|first=Paris|website=parismatch.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> A former escort colleague of Zahia, known as Sarah, claims that she and Zahia were part of an international pimping ring headed by Yves Bouvier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/societe/justice/proces-zahia-abou-l-homme-assoiffe-de-notoriete-derriere-le-scandale_1314932.html|title=Proc\u00e8s Zahia: Abou, l'homme assoiff\u00e9 de notori\u00e9t\u00e9 derri\u00e8re le scandale|date=2014-01-20|website=LExpress.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtl.fr/actu/justice-faits-divers/un-temoignage-relance-l-affaire-zahia-7800147061|title=Un t\u00e9moignage relance l'affaire Zahia|website=RTL.fr|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/lifestyle-fashion/stylenews/mademoiselle-zahia-takes-london-1230977.html|title=Mademoiselle Zahia takes London|last=March 2020|first=2|website=www.femalefirst.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bouvier, Yves}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss art dealers]]\n[[Category:Swiss businesspeople]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:People from Geneva]]\n", "name_user": "Trappist the monk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDispute with Dmitry Rybolovlev:remove 'invisible' characters from cs1|2 template parameters; (1\u00d7 NBSP)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yves_Bouvier"}
